  "issue_title": "[bug] security: validate_inference_route prefix check accepts non-loopback hostnames",
  "issue_body": "# [bug] security: validate_inference_route prefix check accepts non-loopback hostnames\n\n**Component:** `crates/genie-core/src/security/sandbox.rs`\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n`validate_inference_route()` is documented as SSRF prevention for LLM HTTP calls (\u201cGeniePod only allows LLM calls to local endpoints\u201d). It uses `host.starts_with(\"127.\")` after naive host extraction, so hostnames such as `127.evil.com` or `127.0.0.1.attacker.com` pass validation but resolve to attacker-controlled addresses.\n\nThis is the same prefix-trick class as [#301](https://github.com/GeniePod/genie-claw/issues/301) (SearXNG `is_local_base_url`), but in the inference-route guard. Once [#306](https://github.com/GeniePod/genie-claw/issues/306) wires this function at LLM client construction, misconfigured or malicious URLs would bypass the intended local-only policy.\n\n---\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n```106:117:genie-claw/crates/genie-core/src/security/sandbox.rs\npub fn validate_inference_route(url: &str) -> Result<(), String> {\n    let host = extract_host(url);\n\n    match host.as_str() {\n        \"127.0.0.1\" | \"localhost\" | \"::1\" | \"[::1]\" => Ok(()),\n        h if h.starts_with(\"127.\") => Ok(()), // 127.0.0.0/8 loopback\n        _ => Err(format!( ... )),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nExamples that incorrectly return **Ok**:\n\n| URL | DNS resolves to |\n|-----|-----------------|\n| `http://127.evil.com:8080/v1` | Attacker-controlled |\n| `http://127.0.0.1.attacker.com:8080/v1` | Attacker-controlled |\n| `http://localhost.evil.com:8080/v1` | Attacker-controlled (exact `localhost` match misses this) |\n\n`extract_host()` also mishandles bracketed IPv6 (`[::1]`) and userinfo (`user@host`).\n\n---\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nParse the authority host and allow only true loopback targets:\n\n- Literal `localhost` (no extra DNS labels)\n- Parsed `IpAddr::is_loopback()` (covers `127.0.0.0/8`, `::1`, etc.)\n- Reject hostnames that merely **start with** loopback-looking prefixes\n\n---\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n```markdown\n1. Call `validate_inference_route(\"http://127.evil.com:8080/v1\")` in a unit test.\n2. Observe `Ok(())` \u2014 should be `Err`.\n3. Compare with `validate_inference_route(\"http://127.0.0.1:8080/v1\")` which correctly returns `Ok`.\n```\n\n---\n\n## Impact\n\n- **Confidentiality / integrity:** after #306 lands, a misconfigured LLM service URL could point outbound inference traffic at an external host while operators believe the guard enforces loopback-only.\n- Severity: **Medium\u2013High** (latent until wiring; same class as #301).\n\n---\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nReplace prefix matching with parsed host validation (`IpAddr::is_loopback()`), tighten `extract_host()` for IPv6 brackets and userinfo, add regression tests for suffix-trick hostnames.\n\n---\n\n## Additional context\n\n- Distinct from #306 (function not called in production) \u2014 this is weak validation inside the guard itself.\n- Orthogonal to #301 (web_search SearXNG path) and #303 (inbound HTTP Host spoof).\n",
